In Machine Learning, Lasso, Ridge, L1, and L2 are techniques used to prevent overfitting by adding a penalty to the model coefficients. This process is called Regularization.

1️⃣ Why Regularization is Needed

When we build models like Linear Regression, the model may overfit if there are too many features.

Example dataset:

House Size	Bedrooms	Distance	Price
1200	2	5 km	50L
1500	3	3 km	70L
2000	4	2 km	95L

Regression formula:


Price=b0+b1(Size)+b2(Bedrooms)+b3(Distance)

If coefficients become very large, the model may fit training data perfectly but fail on new data.

Regularization penalizes large coefficients.

2️⃣ L1 Regularization (Lasso)

📌 Formula


Loss=MSE+λ∑∣w∣

Where

MSE = Mean Squared Error

λ (lambda) = penalty strength

|w| = absolute value of coefficients

📌 Key Feature

L1 can make some coefficients exactly zero.

This means automatic feature selection.

Example

Suppose we have features:

Feature	Coefficient
Size	0.8
Bedrooms	0
Distance	0.4

Here Bedrooms feature becomes 0 → removed from model.

So Lasso selects only important features.

Python Example
from sklearn.linear_model import Lasso

model = Lasso(alpha=0.1)
model.fit(X_train, y_train)

print(model.coef_)
