Penalty uses square of coefficients.

📌 Key Feature

Coefficients never become zero

They just become smaller

Example
Feature	Coefficient
Size	0.6
Bedrooms	0.3
Distance	0.2

All features remain in the model.

Python Example
from sklearn.linear_model import Ridge

model = Ridge(alpha=0.1)
model.fit(X_train, y_train)

print(model.coef_)
4️⃣ Lasso vs Ridge
Feature	Lasso (L1)	Ridge (L2)
Penalty	Absolute values	Squared values
Feature Selection	Yes	No
Coefficients	Some become 0	Small but not zero
Best Use	Many useless features	Multicollinearity
5️⃣ Real-Time Example (Healthcare Project)

Imagine Medical Coding Automation (LLM + ML) where we predict ICD codes from clinical notes.

Features extracted:

Age

Blood pressure

Cholesterol

Smoking status

Family history

2000 NLP features from clinical text

Many features are not useful.

Using Lasso

Lasso removes irrelevant features.

Example result:

Feature	Coefficient
Blood pressure	0.9
Cholesterol	0.5
Smoking	0.7
Family history	0
Feature_134	0

So Lasso selects only important medical signals.

Using Ridge

Ridge keeps all features but reduces their impact.

Useful when features are highly correlated (common in medical data).

6️⃣ Visual Intuition

Without Regularization

Size coefficient = 120
Bedrooms = 80
Distance = -95

Model becomes unstable.

With Ridge

Size = 10
Bedrooms = 6
Distance = -8

More stable and generalizable.

7️⃣ Interview Answer (Short)

Ridge (L2)

Uses squared penalty

Reduces coefficients but not zero

Lasso (L1)

Uses absolute penalty

Performs feature selection

✅ One-line summary

L1 (Lasso) → Feature selection

L2 (Ridge) → Shrinks coefficients

